          a bit more painterly, or even a character.
        </p>
        <p>
          One of the first jobs I ever held was at a custom printing shop, where
          I had the opportunity to clean up logos that would be transferred to
          film. Since then, I've stuck with the same core philosophies: Ensure
          that the art doesn't become muddy at small sizes. If it had text, make
          sure that it's readable at various distances, and start the work in
          b&amp;w, even if it ends up in color (this helps keep the contrast in
          check).
